  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. These laws and frameworks are established through international agreements, conventions, and the efforts of global organizations. Some of the key international instruments and organizations involved in combating money laundering include:\n\n1. **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Also known as the Vienna Convention, this was one of the first international agreements to address money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n\n2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: Established in 1989 by the G7 countries, FATF is a global intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF publishes a series of recommendations (the FATF Recommendations) that are widely adopted by countries around the world.\n\n3. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Known as the Palermo Convention, this treaty includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n\n4. **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: This convention includes measures to prevent and combat corruption, including the laundering of proceeds of corruption.\n\n5. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**: While not specifically a law, the Basel Committee, through its \"Core Principles for Effective Banking Supervision,\" includes guidelines for banks to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures.\n\n6. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**: These institutions assist countries in adopting AML frameworks and practices, often in line with FATF Recommendations.\n\n7. **European Union Directives on Money Laundering**: The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives that member states are required to transpose into their national laws.\n\nCountries that are part of these international agreements or that have joined international organizations with AML mandates are typically required to implement these standards into their domestic legal systems. This often involves enacting legislation that criminalizes money laundering, requiring financial institutions to perform customer due diligence, report suspicious activities, and maintain records; and establishing financial intelligence units to analyze and disseminate financial information.\n\nNon-compliance with these international standards can lead to diplomatic and economic sanctions, including being placed on a \"blacklist\" or \"grey list\" by the FATF, which can affect a country's access to international finance and increase scrutiny by foreign entities.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
